[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]'Of course, the judicial review system is an important way to right wrongs, but it is not a      promotional tool for countless Left-wing ca
[normal]mpaigners. So that is why we are publishing our       proposals for change. We will protect the parts of judicial review that are essential to justice,     but stop the abuse.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal] Britain cannot afford to allow a culture of Left-wing-dominated, single-issu
[normal]e activism to hold 
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal] back our country from investing in infrastructure and
[normal] new sources of energy and from
[normal]  
[normal]              
[normal]bringing
[normal] down the cost of our welfare state.
[normal]We need to make decisions quicker and respond to issues more quickly in what is a true
[normal] global race.
[normal] 
[normal]The Left does not understand this, and believes that our society can do everything for
[normal]  e
[normal]veryone,
[normal] a
[normal]nd that 
[normal]those who work hard to get on in life should pick up the tab.
[normal] 
[normal]They want more money for public services, but at the same time to be able to halt 
[normal]the investments which can deliver the wealth that pays for those services.
[normal]I
[normal]n proposing these changes, I will no doubt be accused of killing justice and destroying Magna
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Carta
[normal]. Although as the great old lady of British law is approaching her 800th birthd
[normal]ay, and the 
[normal] 
[normal]judicial review system is barely 40, I’m not sure that argument stacks up. But in proposing  these changes, I know we will be doing the right thing for Britain.' 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Whilst the Lord Chancellor’s comments may have been in some part specific to ju
[normal]dicial reviews brought on environmental/plann
[normal]ing interests the NAYJ has
[normal] concern that he expresses his  views in political terms with a heavy regard towards economical value for money. Judicial review is not political and certainly not a left-win
[normal]g mechanism. It is a means of 
[normal]holding those who make and uphold the law to account
[normal] and ensure the correct and just decisions are made, not just speedy ones
[normal]. We sincerely hope that the
[normal] Lord Chancellor regrets these 
[normal] comments in light of our submissions in o
[normal]ur response on behalf of the need for access to justice  on behalf of Britain’s children.
