[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]       matter of course 
[normal]rather than just in exceptional circumstances, t
[normal]he NAYJ be
[normal]lieves this is a matter for the     
[normal]       
[normal]court to decide on each individual case. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Wasted Costs Orders  [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“Legal representatives will, of course, whether barristers or solicitors, advice clients of the perceived weakness of their case and of the risk of failure. But clients are free to reject advice and insist that cases be litigated. It is rarely if ever safe
[normal] for a court to assume that a hopeless case is being litigated on the advice of the lawyers involved. They are there to present the case; it is (as Samuel Johnson unforgettably pointed out) for the judge and not the lawyers to judge it.” 
[normal]              
[normal]Given that, as 
[normal]noted previously, the legal issues involved in representing children are 
[normal]frequently more complex any increased threat of WCO might result in young people in trouble with the law finding it increasingly difficult to secure representation for judicial 
[normal]review.
